  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key aspects include:\n\n1. Financial institutions must:\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Verify customer identities\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Screen for potential money laundering activities\n\n2. Major regulatory frameworks include:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (United States)\n- EU Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) international standards\n\n3. Penalties for non-compliance can include:\n- Significant financial fines\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Loss of business licenses\n\n4. Regulated sectors typically include:\n- Banks\n- Credit unions\n- Investment firms\n- Money transfer services\n- Cryptocurrency exchanges\n\nThese regulations aim to combat financial crimes like terrorism financing, drug trafficking, and tax evasion by making it harder to move illegal funds through the financial system.",
